issue.title: Crash encountered with more than one node in the graph
issue.body:
I execute a query on my RedisGraph and get a crash.

Redis version:7.2.0
RedisGraph version: v2.12.9
operating system: windows 10
API：Cypher version 9
query:CREATE (c0) DELETE c0 WITH * MATCH (),() RETURN 1
error message:"Reached the max retries per request limit (which is 1). Refer to "maxRetriesPerRequest" option for details."

To reproduce:
CREATE (),();
CREATE (c0) DELETE c0 WITH * MATCH (),() RETURN 1;

It's worth noting that the database works fine when there is only one node in the graph, but crashes when there are two nodes in the graph.

Actual behavior:
The query failed and the redisgraph container exited abnormally with the error message.

comment.body: May I ask a question that what is the current LOC of RedisGraph?

issue.title: Incorrect evaluation of ANY clause referencing list from previous WITH
issue.body:
I'll try and build a simpler case for this when I get chance
It's the same for all the list functions any/none etc.

This query returns (incorrectly 110 results) incuding items not in the ids list
```
MATCH (d:Diagram) 
WITH [i IN collect(d.id) | i+'.dxf'] as ids 
MATCH (n{class: 'ConnectionTable'}) 
WITH *, any(i IN ids WHERE i = n.connectionTableTargetDiagramName) as exists 
WHERE exists 
RETURN n.connectionTableTargetDiagramName
```

This one correctly returns 24
```
MATCH (d:Diagram) 
WITH [i IN collect(d.id) | i+'.dxf'] as ids 
MATCH (n{class: 'ConnectionTable'}) 
WITH *, [i IN ids WHERE i = n.connectionTableTargetDiagramName| i] as exists 
WHERE exists <> [] 
RETURN n.connectionTableTargetDiagramName
```

AFAICS these should be equivalent, albeit the first one should do less work

Profile dump shows the filter is just not doing much of anything in the first case

```
127.0.0.1:6379> GRAPH.PROFILE "g" "MATCH (d:Diagram) WITH [i IN collect(d.id) | i+'.dxf'] as ids MATCH (n{class: 'ConnectionTable'}) WITH *, any(i IN ids WHERE i = n.connectionTableTargetDiagramName) as exists WHERE exists RETURN n.connectionTableTargetDiagramName"
1) "Results | Records produced: 110, Execution time: 0.006719 ms"
2) "    Project | Records produced: 110, Execution time: 0.030187 ms"
3) "        Filter | Records produced: 110, Execution time: 0.011820 ms"
4) "            Project | Records produced: 139, Execution time: 0.122531 ms"
5) "                Filter | Records produced: 139, Execution time: 1.053165 ms"
6) "                    All Node Scan | (n) | Records produced: 3647, Execution time: 1.037812 ms"
7) "                        Aggregate | Records produced: 1, Execution time: 0.024629 ms"
8) "                            Node By Label Scan | (d:Diagram) | Records produced: 11, Execution time: 0.002310 ms"
127.0.0.1:6379> GRAPH.PROFILE "g" "MATCH (d:Diagram) WITH [i IN collect(d.id) | i+'.dxf'] as ids MATCH (n{class: 'ConnectionTable'}) WITH *, [i IN ids WHERE i = n.connectionTableTargetDiagramName| i] as exists WHERE exists <> [] RETURN n.connectionTableTargetDiagramName"
1) "Results | Records produced: 24, Execution time: 0.002380 ms"
2) "    Project | Records produced: 24, Execution time: 0.069515 ms"
3) "        Filter | Records produced: 24, Execution time: 0.026150 ms"
4) "            Project | Records produced: 139, Execution time: 0.208002 ms"
5) "                Filter | Records produced: 139, Execution time: 1.107909 ms"
6) "                    All Node Scan | (n) | Records produced: 3647, Execution time: 1.084787 ms"
7) "                        Aggregate | Records produced: 1, Execution time: 0.064686 ms"
8) "                            Node By Label Scan | (d:Diagram) | Records produced: 11, Execution time: 0.002230 ms"
```

comment.body:
From some tests today, I believe this is probably related to null handling
if connectionTableTargetDiagramName is null in the original query, the Any returns true
any(i IN ids WHERE i = n.connectionTableTargetDiagramName)
This is a somewhat surprising result, given it's a direct equality check, and the ids list does not contain null but I assume it's related to null handling. And likely applies to the other list operations.
Adding a direct check for null before the equality works around the issue.

pull_request.title: Moving from circleci to gha WRT benchmark flows
pull_request.body:
This PR removes the usage of circleci for benchmark workflows. It introduces 3 github actions:
- One for merges to version and master/main branches
- One for triggering benchmarks during PR work
- One for triggering nightly benchmarks once a week

It requires the following secrets to be present among the repo action secrets:
- PERFORMANCE_RTS_AUTH
- PERFORMANCE_RTS_HOST
- PERFORMANCE_RTS_PORT
- PERFORMANCE_WH_TOKEN
- PERFORMANCE_GH_TOKEN
- PERFORMANCE_EC2_ACCESS_KEY
- PERFORMANCE_EC2_SECRET_KEY
- PERFORMANCE_EC2_REGION
- PERFORMANCE_EC2_PRIVATE_PEM

Checks:
- [x] confirm secrets are present
- [x] confirm `circleci config check` outputs a valid config file
- [x] confirm the comment with performance info is present on this PR
    - https://github.com/RedisGraph/RedisGraph/pull/3209#issuecomment-1759279746

issue.title: Node created failed when adding "WITH *"
issue.body:
I execute two queries on my empty RedisGraph and get an error.

Redis version:7.2.0
RedisGraph version: v2.12.10
operating system: windows 11
API：Cypher version 9

Steps to reproduce:

Ⅰ: WITH 1 AS a0 WHERE NULL CREATE () WITH * RETURN 1
Ⅱ: WITH 1 AS a0 WHERE NULL CREATE () RETURN 1


I think these two queries are equivalent, but the first create no node while the second creates a node(just remove the "WITH *").

issue.title: Crash about using List Comprehension in UNWIND clause
issue.body:
I execute a query on my RedisGraph and get a crash.

Redis version:7.2.0
RedisGraph version: v2.12.10
operating system: windows 11
API：Cypher version 9
error message:"Reached the max retries per request limit (which is 1). Refer to "maxRetriesPerRequest" option for details."

To reproduce:
CREATE (),(),(),()
MATCH () UNWIND [[x IN [1,NULL]]] AS a0 MERGE (n0) RETURN 1

Actual behavior:
The query failed and the redisgraph container exited abnormally with the error message.

pull_request.title: Moving from circleci to gha WRT benchmark flows
pull_request.body:
This PR removes the usage of circleci for benchmark workflows. It introduces 3 github actions:
- One for merges to version and master/main branches
- One for triggering benchmarks during PR work
- One for triggering nightly benchmarks once a week

It requires the following secrets to be present among the repo action secrets:
- PERFORMANCE_RTS_AUTH
- PERFORMANCE_RTS_HOST
- PERFORMANCE_RTS_PORT
- PERFORMANCE_WH_TOKEN
- PERFORMANCE_GH_TOKEN
- PERFORMANCE_EC2_ACCESS_KEY
- PERFORMANCE_EC2_SECRET_KEY
- PERFORMANCE_EC2_REGION
- PERFORMANCE_EC2_PRIVATE_PEM

Checks:
- [x] confirm secrets are present
- [x] confirm `circleci config check` outputs a valid config file
- [x] confirm the comment with performance info is present on this PR
    - https://github.com/RedisGraph/RedisGraph/pull/3209#issuecomment-1759279746
